{"query": "What actions can be taken on European farms with sandy-loam soils to improve soil structure?", "summary": "Several actions can improve soil structure on European farms with sandy-loam soils. Soil amendments are effective, including adding organic processing wastes or their composts which improve soil structure and reduce soil loss according to trials from Spain and the UK (Action 891). Fresh plant material or crop remains can be incorporated, with one study from India finding improved soil structure when straw was incorporated (Action 910). Manures and agricultural composts increase soil organic matter, create larger soil aggregations and have positive effects on soil physical properties according to studies from Denmark and Germany (Action 911). Mixed organic and inorganic amendments can be more effective than inorganic fertilizers alone, with one controlled trial from India finding mixed amendments more effective at reducing soil crack size in dry soil (Action 902). 

Cover crops improve soil structure when fields are empty, with three randomized studies from Denmark, Turkey and the UK finding that growing cover crops improved soil structure, including higher soil porosity, interconnectivity and lower soil resistance (Action 898). Adding mulch to crops improves soil structure and increases soil organic matter according to trials from Canada, Poland and Spain (Action 887). Retaining crop residues increases soil organic carbon and nitrogen, with two randomized trials from Australia and China finding these benefits (Action 907).

Tillage modifications also improve soil structure. Changing tillage practices, specifically reducing tillage, increases soil organic carbon and organic matter with improved soil structure, as found in twelve studies from Australia, Canada, China, Europe, Japan and the USA (Action 906). Controlling traffic and timing reduces compaction and increases soil porosity, with five trials from Europe and Australia finding less compaction, reduced runoff and increased water filtration (Action 899). Soil can also be amended with bacteria or fungi, with one controlled trial from Turkey finding increased soil organic matter content under mycorrhizal-inoculated compost applications (Action 888).", "action_ids": ["891","910","898","902","911","906","887","899","907","888"]}

