{
  "query": "How do the effects of cover crops on soil organic matter differ between studies in Europe and the USA?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, studies from both Europe and the USA show positive effects of cover crops on soil organic matter, but with some regional differences in findings and consistency.\n\n**European Studies:**\nFrom action 1367, studies from France found more organic matter in soils with ground cover compared to soils without ground cover, with permanent ground cover showing more organic matter than temporary ground cover in some comparisons. Studies from Spain consistently found more organic matter in soils with seeded cover crops compared to bare soils, particularly when cover crops were incorporated into the soil. Italian studies from action 1345 found more organic matter in soils with winter cover crops compared to soils without them, though one study from Italy found inconsistent differences (sometimes more, sometimes less). From action 898, European studies (including one controlled, replicated trial) found no marked effect on soil organic matter levels, while one replicated study from Denmark found increased soil carbon levels under cover crops.\n\n**USA Studies:**\nFrom action 1367, USA studies found more organic matter in soils with ground cover compared to soils without ground cover in some or all comparisons, with similar amounts of organic matter in soils with resident vegetation or seeded cover crops. From action 1345, USA studies consistently found more organic matter (mostly measured as carbon) in soils with winter cover crops compared to soils without them in some or all comparisons. Action 898 reports that USA studies found increased nitrogen levels, increased carbon, and increased nitrates under cover crops. From action 897, one controlled trial from the USA (alongside studies from India and South Africa) found that soil organic matter increased under cover crops, while one trial from Germany found no effect.\n\n**Key Differences:**\nEuropean studies show more mixed results, with some finding no marked effects on soil organic matter levels, while USA studies more consistently show positive effects. Italian studies specifically show inconsistent differences in some cases, whereas USA studies typically find increases in soil organic matter. Both regions show benefits when cover crops are incorporated into soil, with European studies particularly emphasizing the advantage of permanent over temporary ground cover.",
