{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and drawbacks of using crop rotation on farms in Canada?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, crop rotation on Canadian farms shows several documented benefits. Studies from Canada found that crop rotation reduced pest populations and crop diseases in at least one year or site, increased crop yield in some years with certain rotation crops, increased profit, and required fewer insecticide treatments (Action 719). Canadian studies also showed that including legumes in crop rotations increased the number of microbes and diversity of soil animals, and including forage crops in rotations reduced rainwater runoff and soil loss (Action 857). Additionally, studies from Canada found increased soil organic carbon under crop rotation, particularly when legumes were included, and increased soil organic matter (Action 857).\n\nHowever, some documented drawbacks exist. One study found pest populations increased in crop rotation, and studies found both increases and decreases in pest populations depending on rotation crops used and other treatments (Action 719). Additionally, some studies found yield increases and decreases depending on rotation crops used (Action 719). Other research found less organic matter in soils with crop rotations compared to continuous crops in some comparisons, inconsistent differences in nitrogen levels, and less phosphorus in soils with crop rotations in some comparisons (Action 1368).",
